  {
    "speaker": "interviewee",
    "tag": "KAY RONEC",
    "text": "I am very pleased that Mom decided to do this project. Until about a year ago, she never spoke about her experiences of the Holocaust. It must have been so painful that she buried it deeply inside herself. An incident a year ago made her start talking about it, and a couple of months ago, Jana visited the Holocaust Museum, and as a result, wrote a beautiful essay-- which made Mom realize how important it is to share her experiences with the next generations. Thank, you Mom, for doing it. I think it's great. I also wanted to make a comment which struck me only very recently. And that this is that I think we, as a family, are very lucky, especially us kids. We've got, Greg, Margaret, and I, have three cousins. One of them lives in Australia and two of them live in France. However, one of our cousins is married to a lady whose parents migrated to Australia in between the two wars, and they have 28 cousins, first cousins. And maybe if the Holocaust didn't happen, maybe would've we would have had as many cousins, or even more. That's what we have missed out on.",
